    <article id="Lec19">
        <header class="html-article-header">
            <h2><span class="html-lec-heading">Lecture 19: Introduction to HTML </span></h2>
        </header>
        <p class="sec-para-main">HTML is a markup language not a full programming language. It stands for
            <i>Hyper
                Text Markup
                Language</i>.
            HTML was originally developed for marking research papers. The main idea behind developing HTML was
            to
            indicate how the document should be presented and structured in a browser i.e how to make a text
            bold,
            italize etc, it is done by using HTML tags. HTML adds annotations to a simple text. HTML
            holds the content, the very basic of your website. HTML is used to indicate to the browser to
            how it should format the document. Web browsers make sense of HTML tags and display it.
        </p>
    </article>
    <article id="Lec20">
        <header class="html-article-header">
            <h2><span class="html-lec-heading">Lecture 20: Our first HTML page(B tag intro)</span></h2>
        </header>
        <p class="sec-para-main"> In our first HTML page we get introduced to <code class="html-tags">&ltb></code>
            tag which is used
            to
            indicate that whatever is inside the tag should be displayed in bold. To bold a text just use <code
                class="html-tags">&ltb></code> tag and some text inside it. The syntax for <code
                class="html-tags">&ltb></code> tag is -
            "<code class="html-tags">&ltb></code>some text<code class="html-tags">&lt/b></code>"
        </p>
        <section class="extra-info">
            <h3>Extra Info-</h3>
            <p>Bold tag <code class="html-tags">&ltb></code> does not contain any semantic significance, it is
                just used to style an element as bold. Whereas <code class="html-tags">&ltstrong></code> tag
                specifies to the browser that this element is important and should be stressed. It all makes a
                difference when using with screen reader. Same goes for <code class="html-tags">&lti></code> and
                <code class="html-tags">&ltem></code> tags in HTML. Put simply, when you use <code
                    class="html-tags">&ltb></code> tag to style your element you are just bolding the
                text but when you use <code class="html-tags">&ltstrong></code> tag then you are indicating to
                the browser that this element is important and should be stressed. Although visually both the
                elements might look same but they have semantical differences. Also if you need to style more than a
                single word in between your elements then it's better to use CSS for that, it separates HTML for
                content and CSS for styling this is called separation of concern which we will learn about later in
                the course.
                <span class="src-link">
                    <span>Source -</span> <a
                        href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/271743/whats-the-difference-between-b-and-strong-i-and-em">SO</a>
                    <a href="https://www.w3.org/International/questions/qa-b-and-i-tags#quickanswer">W3C</a>
                </span>
            </p>
        </section>
    </article>
