    <article id="Lec25">
        <header class="html-article-header">
            <h2><span class="html-lec-heading">Lecture 25: HTML boilerplate</span></h2>
        </header>
        <p class="sec-para-main">HTML boilerplate is like the skeleton of the page, as it gives structure to the
            page. First element
            of
            Boilerplate is <code class="html-tags">&lt!DOCTYPE html></code> which tells the broswer that the
            document is a HTML document without it the browser may <span class="i-word">interpret</span> your
            document differently. Second element is <code class="html-tags">&lthtml></code> tag, although it is
            not
            necessary to put this tag as it is implicitly put by the browser. But still it's a good practice to
            keep
            it if you share your code then it is read easily.<code class="html-tags">&lthtml></code> tag
            contains
            <code class="html-tags">&lthead></code>
            and
            <code class="html-tags">&ltbody></code> tag inside it. <code class="html-tags">&lthead></code> tag
            contains metadata about the document i.e. links to your stylesheets, external font-file etc. It also
            contains the title of the document which is displayed on the tab of the page. The body tag can
            contains
            rest of the content displayed on your webpage. Although it is not necessary to include all these
            tags , but it is a good practice to include them to avoid misinterpretation by any browser and to
            make things easier for other developers.
            <span class="src-link">
                <span>Source -</span>
                <a href="https://html.spec.whatwg.org/#optional-tags">HTML spec</a>
                <a
                    href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/5641997/is-it-necessary-to-write-head-body-and-html-tags">SO1</a>
                <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/6076432/why-do-i-need-a-doctype-what-does-it-do">SO2</a>
            </span>
        </p>
    </article>
